  "summary": "## Iteration 2 Review — #614 (1125ded → e7ceae3)\n\n**Aggregate Rating: 3/5**\nAll B1–B3 and most W fixes verified correct. One iter-1 fix was applied asymmetrically (W5 canonical env template), one data...",
  "feedback": "## Iteration 2 Review — #614 (1125ded → e7ceae3)\n\n**Aggregate Rating: 3/5**\nAll B1–B3 and most W fixes verified correct. One iter-1 fix was applied asymmetrically (W5 canonical env template), one data-loss lockstep gap is newly exposed, and the B2 lockstep tests use relational-only assertions that weaken their contract. No new blocking issues, but the canonical W5 omission and CONFLUENCE/JIRA data-loss warrant treatment before merge.\n\n---\n\n### Iter-1 Fix Verification\n\n| Fix | Status | Notes |\n|-----|--------|-------|\n| B1 — AUXILIARY_SLOTS validation + dupe-role check | ✅ Correct | Exact-string membership; newline-padded roles fail before template sees them |\n| B2 — TestLegacyCanonicalLockstep | ⚠️ Partial | Tests present but relational-only — see W-test-* below |\n| B3 — canonical bedrock-aux test | ✅ Correct | AWS triplet (access_key, secret_key, region) asserted in canonical path |\n| W1 — default_title_gen_map threading | ✅ Correct | Both template families agree on title_generation shadowing |\n| W2 — _seen_type_keys.update before cred guard | ✅ Correct | Primary-wins unconditional registration is sound |\n| W3 — _explicit_aux sorted by role | ✅ Correct | dictsort lockstep verified across both families |\n| W5 — CR/LF/NUL on conflict _ctype | ⚠️ Asymmetric | Applied to legacy `hermes.env.j2` only; canonical `hermes-env.canonical.j2:30` still unfiltered |\n\n---\n\n### New Findings\n\n#### Warnings\n\n**W-canonical-env-unfiltered** *(confirmed by 3/4 specialists)*\n`hermes-env.canonical.j2:30` renders `{{ _c.type }}` with no sanitization filter. Today `_c.type` is validated against `_HERMES_SUPPORTED_PROVIDERS` by `render_hermes()` before `_build_provider_env_views` runs, so there is no live injection path through the production code. However: the legacy template now has defense-in-depth at render time; the canonical template does not. Any test helper or future caller that invokes `_build_provider_env_views` directly without first routing through the `render_hermes` whitelist gate (e.g. `_legacy_render()` in the lockstep suite) would produce an unsanitized `_c.type` in the generated `.env` WARNING comment. The asymmetry in posture is the real issue.\n**Fix:** `{{ _c.type | replace('\\n','') | replace('\\r','') | replace('\\x00','') }}` on that line — matches the legacy filter exactly.\n\n**W-lockstep-confluence-jira-filter** *(registry specialist)*\n`CONFLUENCE_SPACES_FILTER` and `JIRA_PROJECTS_FILTER` are conditionally emitted inside the MCP server `env:` block in `hermes-config.yaml.j2` (legacy configure path). The canonical render path (`hermes-config.canonical.yaml.j2`) has no equivalent: `atlassian_views` in `render.py:938-947` is built from only five keys; the two filter fields are not threaded through. A `clawctl agent configure` (legacy path) that writes these filter settings is followed by a `clawctl agent sync` (canonical path) that silently replaces the MCP block without them — data loss on every sync cycle.\n**Fix:** Add `confluence_spaces_filter` and `jira_projects_filter` to `atlassian_views` in `render.py`; emit them conditionally in `hermes-config.canonical.yaml.j2` mirroring the legacy pattern. Add a configure→sync round-trip lockstep test.\n\n**W-false-positive-bedrock-warning** *(lifecycle specialist)*\n`hermes.env.j2` emits `# WARNING: multiple bedrock providers attached with different API keys` when `_key_compare` is `'|'` (primary has empty credentials, aux has real ones). The primary-wins invariant is correct, but the warning text misrepresents the situation — the primary is missing creds, not carrying different ones. Operators chasing this during a missing-secret failure are sent on the wrong trace; the canonical path already raises `AgentConfigError` on missing bedrock primary creds, so this is a legacy-template-only operator-UX issue.\n**Fix:** Distinguish `primary-has-no-creds` from `same-type-different-keys` in the legacy env template's bedrock branch; skip `_conflicts.append` and surface a distinct comment/marker.\n\n---\n\n#### Test Assertion Weaknesses (B2 partial credit)\n\n**W-test-ordering-absoluteness**\n`test_multi_aux_yaml_ordering_matches` asserts `list(legacy_keys) == list(canonical_keys)` only. If both families emit `['vision', 'title_generation', 'web_extract']` (wrong order), the test passes. The alphabetical-sort contract is never verified independently.\n**Fix:** Add `assert list(canonical_yaml['auxiliary'].keys()) == ['title_generation', 'vision', 'web_extract']` alongside the mutual-equality assertion.\n\n**W-test-tg-shadow-independence**\n`test_explicit_title_generation_lockstep` asserts `legacy_yaml['auxiliary'] == canonical_yaml['auxiliary']`. It does not independently verify (a) the explicit model appears, or (b) the default model (`claude-haiku-4-5-20251001`) does not appear. Both families double-emitting a default block would still match.\n**Fix:** Add model-value and default-absent assertions to both family branches.\n\n**W-test-env-lockstep-multi**\n`test_env_var_key_set_matches_single_provider` covers only the no-aux path. No multi-provider env key-set lockstep test exists. A regression where canonical emits `OPENROUTER_API_KEY` for a multi-aux config but legacy does not (or vice versa) is undetected.\n**Fix:** Add `test_env_var_key_set_matches_multi_provider` using the same `vision + web_extract` config as the ordering test, asserting `_emitted_env_keys(legacy_env) == _emitted_env_keys(canonical_env)`.\n\n**W-test-bedrock-dedup-uncovered**\nThe W2 bedrock-primary + bedrock-auxiliary dedup path in `_build_provider_env_views` is exercised by no test — neither same-creds (single triplet, no WARNING) nor different-creds (primary wins, WARNING present, aux key absent).\n**Fix:** Add two tests in `TestCanonicalMultiProvider`: (1) same creds → single `AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID`, no WARNING; (2) different creds → primary's `ACCESS_KEY` present, aux's absent, WARNING comment present.\n\n---\n\n#### Suggestions\n\n| # | Location | Issue |\n|---|----------|-------|\n| S1 | `render.py:386` | Duplicate deferred import of `AUXILIARY_SLOTS`; consolidate into existing block at line 251-253 |\n| S2 | `tests/…:485` | `_legacy_render()` bypasses `_pa.validate()` — either add the validate call or comment the invariant gap |\n| S3 | `render.py:860` | `render_hermes()` validates primary type but not aux types — unknown aux type silently falls through with no key and no error |\n| S4 | `hermes-config.yaml.j2:13-14` | `yaml_quote` macro doesn't strip CR/LF/NUL before single-quote escaping; NUL truncation risk in ansible path (not injection) |\n| S5 | `render.py:392` | `role = entry.get('role', '')` — not stripped before AUXILIARY_SLOTS check; trailing-space typo yields confusing error message |\n| S6 | Test suite | Add lockstep parity test for a role alphabetically before `title_generation` (e.g. `approval`) to pin default-title_gen-first ordering contract |\n\n---\n\n### Summary for Author\n\n**Must fix before merge:**\n1. Apply W5 CR/LF/NUL filter to `hermes-env.canonical.j2:30` — the asymmetric defense posture between template families is the unfinished half of W5.\n2. Thread CONFLUENCE_SPACES_FILTER / JIRA_PROJECTS_FILTER through `atlassian_views` in `render.py` and emit them in the canonical YAML template — configure→sync data loss is a correctness regression.\n3. Strengthen B2 lockstep tests with absolute assertions on key order, explicit model presence, and multi-provider env key-set equality — relational-only assertions let both families regress together silently.\n4. Add bedrock-bedrock dedup tests (same-creds + different-creds) to cover the W2 branch.\n\n**Can defer:**\n- False-positive bedrock WARNING text (operator UX, correct behavior)\n- S1–S6 suggestions (housekeeping / defense-in-depth, no correctness risk)\n- W4 ollama aux endpoint (acknowledged upstream-verification follow-up from iter-1)",
